data.title: Puig Restores 2025 Growth View After Revenue Climbs on Beauty Demand
data.description:
(16:49 GMT) *Puig 3Q Sales EUR1.3B
(16:50 GMT) *Puig 3Q Sales rose 3.2% on Year
(16:50 GMT) *Analysts Had Seen Puig 3Q Sales at EUR1.26B
(16:51 GMT) *Puig 3Q Fragrance and Fashion Sales Flat on Year at EUR932M
(16:51 GMT) *Puig 3Q Skincare Sales Rose 8.2%
(16:51 GMT) *Puig 3Q Makeup Sales Rose 15%
(17:09 GMT) Puig Restores 2025 Growth View After Revenue Climbs on Beauty Demand

By Joshua Kirby

Jean Paul Gaultier owner Puig Brands restated a growth target for the year after revenue climbed over the third quarter, pointing to a continued recovery in the beauty market.

Barcelona-based Puig, which also counts Carolina Herrera and Nina Ricci among its brands and holds the licenses to others, said revenue grew 3.2% on year to 1.3 billion euros ($1.5 billion) over the three months through September. That marks a slightly better result than the 1.26 billion euros analysts had expected Puig to make over the quarter, according to a poll put together by FactSet ahead of the release.

On the back of the rise in revenue, Puig said it now expects to meet the middle part of a target set out at the start of the year, for 6%-8% like-for-like revenue growth for 2025 as a whole. Puig shares lost ground last month when the company warned that full-year growth would come in at the lower end of that range.

"We approach the holiday season with full confidence in achieving our full-year outlook," Chief Executive Marc Puig said.

The mainstay fragrance and fashion business booked flat sales compared with the same period last year, but the makeup and skincare divisions booked increases of 15% and 8.2%, respectively, suggesting strong demand for beauty and cosmetics in an evolving market.

It comes after Gucci owner Kering earlier this month agreed to sell its beauty business, including cologne brand House Creed and rights to develop fragrances and beauty products for its fashion labels, to French cosmetics giant L'Oreal for around $4.7 billion.

data.title: Coinbase Reports Earnings Today. Why the Crypto Firm Could Break Out of Its Slump. — Barrons.com
data.description:
By Nate Wolf

Coinbase Global reports third-quarter earnings Thursday afternoon, giving the cryptocurrency behemoth a chance to get back on track in what has been a rough second half of the year.

Shares of Coinbase rocketed 52% higher through July, buoyed by rising crypto prices, regulatory momentum, and the company's inclusion in the S&P 500. It's been a slog since then. The stock plummeted 17% on Aug. 1 after second-quarter earnings results showed a 39% drop in transaction revenue — and Coinbase is yet to claw back those losses.

The stock was down 3.3% to $337.09 on Thursday, though it remains up 35% in 2025.

Analysts expect Coinbase to report $1.8 billion in revenue for the third quarter, up 49% from a year ago, per FactSet. Earnings are expected to come in at $1.13 a share, well above 28 cents last year. That growth should show up across the business, from consumer and institutional transactions to subscriptions and services, analysts predict.

H.C. Wainwright, which downgraded Coinbase to a short-term Sell in July a few weeks before the stock's pullback, double-upgraded shares to Buy in a research note Thursday. The firm also lifted its price target for Coinbase shares to $425 from $300.

Crypto trading volumes and the company's "take rate" on transaction fees should drive revenue and profits higher than previously expected, H.C. Wainwright argued.

Coinbase's $2.9 billion acquisition of crypto options exchange Deribit, which closed in August, may also bear fruit. H.C. Wainwright expects Coinbase to post meaningful derivatives trading revenue for the first time.

Looking beyond Thursday, further momentum in Washington, D.C., may be the most critical catalyst for Coinbase.

The Genius Act in late July established a regulatory framework for stablecoins, which are tokens pegged to assets like the U.S. dollar. Coinbase notably takes in revenue as a distribution partner for USDC, the stablecoin issued by Circle Internet Group.

Crypto companies are now waiting for the Senate to pass the Clarity Act, which would divide regulation between the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. Many crypto industry insiders believe the bill, which passed in the House of Representatives in July, will unleash institutional adoption of digital assets. The Clarity Act will likely get the green light from the Senate by the end of 2025, giving a boost to Coinbase shares, H.C. Wainwright argued.

"Our stance has turned back to bullish," H.C. Wainwright analyst Mike Colonnese wrote of Coinbase. "We expect rising crypto asset prices (driven by seasonal strength and accelerating institutional demand) and regulatory tailwinds to drive the stock higher in the last quarter of the year."

H.C. Wainwright's double-upgrade followed a similarly bullish outlook from J.P. Morgan, which upgraded Coinbase to Overweight from Neutral and raised its price target to $404 from $342 last week. Coinbase has many monetization opportunities beyond crypto trading, including its Coinbase One subscription offering, J.P. Morgan said.

That growing diversification means plenty of opportunities to impress — or disappoint — investors on Thursday.

Write to Nate Wolf at nate.wolf@barrons.com

CALGARY, AB / ACCESS Newswire / October 30, 2025 / CANEX Metals Inc. ("Canex") is pleased to report that at its Annual & Special Meeting, held on October 30, 2025, Shane Ebert, Jean-Pierre Jutras, Lesley Hayes, Gregory Hanks and Blair Schultz were re-elected to the Board of Directors. Shareholders also approved fixing the number of directors at five, the appointment of BDO Canada LLP as Auditors and ratified Canex's stock option plan.

About CANEX Metals

CANEX Metals (TSX.V:CANX) is a Canadian junior exploration company focused on advancing it's 100% owned Gold Range Project in Northern Arizona. With several near surface bulk tonnage gold discoveries made to date across a 4 km gold mineralized trend, the Gold Range Project is a compelling early-stage opportunity for investors. CANEX is also advancing the Louise Copper-Gold Porphyry Project in British Columbia. Louise contains a large historic copper-gold resource that has seen very little deep or lateral exploration, offering investors copper and gold discovery potential. CANEX is led by an experienced management team which has made three notable porphyry and bulk tonnage discoveries in North America and is sponsored by Altius Minerals , a large shareholder of the Company.

(17:04 GMT) Universal Music Logs Higher Revenue Despite Slowdown in Subscriptions and Streaming Growth

By Mauro Orru

Universal Music Group posted higher revenue for the third quarter even though growth in subscriptions and streaming services slowed down.

The record label behind Lady Gaga and Taylor Swift reported revenue of 3.02 billion euros ($3.50 billion) for the three months to the end of September, up more than 10% on year at constant currency. Analysts had forecast revenue of 2.92 billion euros, according to consensus estimates by Visible Alpha.

Revenue from subscriptions and streaming grew 6.6% at constant currency to nearly 1.52 billion euros, slightly below analysts' forecast of 7% growth. That marked an slowdown from 8.7% growth that the company recorded for the second quarter.

Adjusted earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization--Universal's preferred measure of profitability--increased to 664 million euros from 621 million euros a year earlier, generating a 22% adjusted margin. Analysts had forecast adjusted Ebitda of 649.4 million euros, according to Visible Alpha.

Write to Mauro Orru at mauro.orru@wsj.com

data.title: Nymex Overview: Oil Futures Flat as Market Reviews U.S.-China Trade Truce — OPIS
data.description:
Crude oil contracts were little changed at midday Thursday, as energy investors reviewed a temporary truce in trade tensions between the U.S. and China following a meeting between President Trump and Chinese leader Xi Jinping.

The NYMEX December West Texas Intermediate contract was about 5cts higher at $60.55/bbl at noon ET and January WTI was up by a similar amount to $60.15/bbl.

The ICE December Brent contract was also 5cts higher at $65/bbl and January Brent was unchanged at $64.30/bbl.

Both oil benchmarks fell about $1 on Wednesday after Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell warned against assuming a December cut in interest rate was all but guaranteed following Wednesday's decision to cut benchmark interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point.

Refined product contracts were mixed. The more-active NYMEX December ULSD contract was up 0.95ct to $2.4065/gal and the November contract was 2.05cts higher at $2.445/gal. The December RBOB contract was down 0.4ct to $1.887/gal and November RBOB was up 0.8ct to $1.982/gal.

Analysts said the temporary agreement between Trump and Xi eases trade tensions between the two nations, but does not address fundamental trade issues.

PBF Energy on Thursday said it expects its 157,000 b/d Martinez refinery in Northern California to return to full output by the end of the year following the completion of seasonal maintenance and repairs to equipment damaged by a February fire.

data.description:
RNS Number : 5762F Aurora UK Alpha PLC 30 October 2025  

AURORA UK ALPHA PLC

(the "Company")

TRANSACTION IN OWN SHARES

Aurora UK Alpha plc announces that in accordance with the authority granted at the Company's Annual General Meeting held on 11 June 2025, it purchased on 30 October 2025 20,000 Ordinary shares of 25p each in the capital of the Company at a price of 259.9402 pence per share. These shares will be held by the Company in treasury.

Following this transaction, the Company holds 3,963,389 Ordinary shares in treasury and has 114,572,742 Ordinary shares in issue, including those in treasury. Therefore, the total number of voting rights in the Company is 110,609,353 and accordingly that figure may be used by shareholders as the denominator for calculations of interests in the Company's voting rights in accordance with the FCA's Disclosure Guidance and Transparency Rules.
